  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue: The crash occurs because
`tryToReuseLCSSAPhi` attempts to compute the difference between two SCEVs, one
of which is a `SCEVCouldNotCompute`. The `SCEVCouldNotCompute` object is
returned by `ScalarEvolution::getPtrToIntExpr` when it cannot convert a pointer
to integer (e.g., due to non-integral pointer types). The `getMinusSCEV` then
calls `getType()` on the `SCEVCouldNotCompute`, triggering an assertion.\n\n2.
Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The log shows the crash happens in
`ScalarEvolution::getMinusSCEV`. The backtrace indicates that `ExitSCEV` is a
`SCEVCouldNotCompute` after the `getPtrToIntExpr` conversion. The IR contains a
pointer in address space 1, which may be a non-integral pointer type, causing
`getPtrToIntExpr` to return `CouldNotCompute`.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: In
`tryToReuseLCSSAPhi`, after converting a pointer phi to integer via
`getPtrToIntExpr`, we must check if the result is `CouldNotCompute`. If it is,
we should skip this phi and continue to the next one. Currently, the code
proceeds to compute `Diff = SE.getMinusSCEV(S, ExitSCEV)` without checking,
leading to the crash.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s): Add a check after line 1243
(or after the conversion) to skip the phi if `ExitSCEV` is a
`SCEVCouldNotCompute`. The edit should be in
`llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/ScalarEvolutionExpander.cpp` at line 1243. We'll
add:\n```cpp\n    if (isa<SCEVCouldNotCompute>(ExitSCEV))\n
continue;\n```\nThis ensures we don't attempt to use a `CouldNotCompute`
SCEV.\n\n5. Conclusion: The fix prevents the crash by skipping phis that cannot
be converted to integer SCEVs. This is safe because we cannot reuse such phis
anyway. The loop will continue to other phis, and if none are usable,
`tryToReuseLCSSAPhi` returns nullptr, falling back to normal expansion.",
